<HEAD>
<TITLE>METEO-FRANCE : The activities </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><CENTER>M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France's activities <HR SIZE=5 ></CENTER></H1>
<P>
<UL TYPE=square>
<LI> <A href="e_metier.html">M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France's expertise</A>
<LI> <A href="e_enjeux.html">Vital for daily life and economic activity</A>
<LI> <A href="e_public.html">M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France's public-service mission</A>
<LI> <A HREF="e_resear.html">M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France and research</A>
<LI> <A HREF="e_specia.html">M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France serves the whole community</A>
</UL>
<P>
<I>Ever since operational meteorology began, M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France public meteorological service has been dedicated to the design, developement, implementation and maintenance of all systems and procedures required for weather forecasting. To this end, it has build up expertise in a wide range of scientific and technical fields, developed ultra-powerful computer models, and established a direct observation network covering France and beyond. <BR> The weather knows no frontiers. M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France therefore plays an active part in the World Meteorological Organization (WMO). Such participation enables it to enhance its skills through exchange of information and involvement in major international research projects on atmospheric phenomena. <BR>
M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France's knowhow and technical expertise make it a world leader in all aspects of meteorology.</I>
<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=40% NOSHADE><P>
<i>The rapid growth of operational meteorology since the end of the 1960s has gone hand in hand with the development of techniques using scientific knowledge gained in a wide variety of fields. The complexity and global nature of the atmosphere call for a rigourous scientif approach.<BR>
Modern meteorology makes use of a whole spectrum of disciplines, including instrumentation, telecommunications, data processing, numerical analysis, remote sensing from the ground and from space, atmospheric physics, fluid mechanics, etc. Weather forecasting and - beyond that - prediction of climate change are based first of all on the availability of powerful observation systems around the world. Next comes the knowhow to analyse observations and to convert them into numerical data for short, medium and long range forecasts. Finally, forecasts have to be adapted to each user category, and made available as appropriate.<BR>
This professional expertise covering many fields has but one aim - that of serving people's daily lives and their economic activities.<BR>
Since its foundation more than a century ago, M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France (as the French national meteorological service was re-named in 1994) has had the primary mission of safeguarding people and property. It has equipped itself with the tools needed to satisfy the requirements and the ethical standards of public service, whilst developing forecasting procedures adapted to various economic activities.</i>
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="/e_index.html"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=43 HEIGHT=43 
SRC="/icons/meteo.gif"></A>
<A HREF="/e_index.html"> M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France's Home Page</A>
<HR SIZE=5>
Copyright &copy; 1995 M&eacute;t&eacute;o-France
</BODY>
