<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>README - Fortran2html 4.0</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER>
<HR size=3>
<H1>README - Fortran2html 4.0</H1>
<HR size=3>
</CENTER>
<PRE>
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        Fortran2html 4.0
        ----------------

                building hypertexted images of fortran programs
                (c) 1996 Meteo-France SCEM/PREVI/COMPAS/GCO

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        0. General Purpose:
        -------------------

        Fortran2html converts your source projects written in FORTRAN
        to the HTML syntax, enabling a fast navigation mode and variables
        tracing as well as miscellaneous operations including multiple
        versions management.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        1. What is the input data?
        --------------------------

        A multi-level directory structure of source files in FORTRAN 77 
        or FORTRAN 90 (as long as you write only external procedures):

        ...../project/dir_1/files
                     /dir_2/files  .h or .F or .anything!
                     /dir_2/dir_2a
                     /dir_2/dir_2a/files
                     /dir_2/dir_2b
                     /dir_2/dir_2b/files
                        .
                        ..
                     /dir_n/files

        The only restriction is that the top level directory project should
        only contain directories and no files for esthetic reasons (and...
        for multiple versions management, see below)!

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        2. What do you retrieve?
        ------------------------

        You retrieve the matching architecture of directories with HTML
        files under:

        $WWWROOT/project/dir_1/files.html
                        /dir_2/dir_2a
                        /dir_2/dir_2a/files.html
                        /dir_2/dir_2b
                        /dir_2/dir_2b/files.html
                          ..
                        /dir_n/files.html
                        /data_1/STOxxx.html files for datatype data_1
                          ..
                        /data_m/STOxxx.html files for datatype data_m
                         main.html  (main entry point)
                         index.html  (top level index)
                        /F2HDico/index.html  (dictionary of modules)

        Hypertexted features are:

                - calling sequences
                - functions
                - backward dependencies
                - variables with status ( argument, read-write use)
                - expand mechanism
                - miscellaneous job mechanism

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        3. Installing Fortran2html
        --------------------------

        A) gunzip and untar the Fortran2html tar file, you retrieve 
           the following contents:

        ./README                the file you are reading

        ./INSTALL               install procedure

        ./bin/f2h_back          job to retrieve original source file
        ./bin/f2h_cgiexpj       job for the cgi-bin location
        ./bin/f2h_cgiexpr       job for the cgi-bin location
        ./bin/f2h_cgijob        job for the cgi-bin location
        ./bin/f2h_cgirun        job for the cgi-bin location
        ./bin/f2h_cgisrc        job for the cgi-bin location
        ./bin/f2h_cgivar        job for the cgi-bin location
        ./bin/f2h_create        main job for creating the html database
        ./bin/f2h_diffcreate    alternative create job with incremental diff
                                between multiple versions

        ./images/               several gif buttons
        ./conf/fort_datp.conf   FORTRAN datatypes and hash values (cf 4)
        ./conf/fort_keyw.conf   FORTRAN keywords

        ./include/              temporarily empty directory

        ./src/*.c *.h           kernel programs of f2h scripts
        ./src/makefile          guess what? edit for changing CC env.

        B) Then run the ./INSTALL procedure which copy scripts and compile
        some of the programs and define the common paths for the f2h scripts
        which are by default:

        HTTPDIR   /usr/users/W3   Http stuff main location
                                  overwritten by the -h option

        CGIBIN    /cgi-bin        cgi binaries location (local path)
                                  overwritten by the -c option

        WWWPATH   $HOME/WWW       central location of WWW stuff
                                  overwritten by the -w option

        BACKPATH  Cycles          extension to WWWPATH for f2h outputs
                                  overwritten by the -b option

        TMPWD     /tmp/f2html     tmp working directory
                                  overwritten by the -t option

        F2HPATH   $PWD            when running INSTALL

        BIN       $F2HPATH/bin    should be added to PATH env variable

        Note that the CGI-BIN scripts repository is defined twice:
                - through the CGI internal env variable defined as
                  CGI=$HTTPDIR/cgi-bin
                - through the local path for http references:
                  CGIBIN=/cgi-bin       (standard location) or 
                  CGIBIN=/login/cgi-bin (user's private location) or
                  CGIBIN=/~login/cgi-bin (global access to user's home)

        WARNING: do not forget the slash at the beginning of CGIBIN.

        *CgiParse* should be installed under $HTTPDIR/bin
        *CgiParse* is a public domain http CERN tool.

        C) Go to the location of the ascii version of your project and
           then run the f2h_create job with the project name (which is
           also the root directory name of the project!) as argument.

                % cd ~/src
                % ls
                test cy13.4 cy14
                % f2h_create -d cy14 > ~/tmp/out_cy14 2>&1 &

           Other optional arguments are:

                -n : to give a project name different of the root dir name
                     ex: f2h_create -d cy14 -n cycle_14

        That's All Folks !!!

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        4. Cross references and f2h_diffcreate
        --------------------------------------

        Fortran2html 4.o handles multiple versions of the same source file
        inside the same "project". It could be usefull for:

        - a project with its bugfix

        - a project built whith multiple releases of the same sources

        - mixing of several projects with a non-null intersection

        Multiple versions of the same module are taken into account whatever
        their location are. However, it appears that in most of the cases,
        users define their versions as the first level of directories.
        According to this condition, the f2h_diffcreate script scans the
        original source location and perform an incremental diff according
        to the hierarchy of versions given in the "-l filename" argument.
        Then a call to f2h_create is automatically performed. Note that
        there is no file removing mechanism in the f2h_diffcreate mechanism:
        a temporary directory is created and links are established with
        selected elements of the original source location.
        
        Example: the original code structure is:

                myproject/version1/src
                                  /include
                         /version2/src
                                  /src/level2
                                  /include
                         /version3/src/
                                  /include

        the priority list file should be something like:

        version3
        version2
        version1

        so that only version3 files which differ from version2 will be
        selected and version2 files which differ from version0. The
        last directory of the list and any directory which is not in this
        list will be completly selected.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        5. Customizing FORTRAN datatypes:
        ---------------------------------

        Before the step C of the previous sequence, you may wish to
        redefine the default datatype classification which is the
        DOCTOR norm with some adjustments.

        The conf/fort_datp.conf file must always have 3 columns:
        
                - prefix of the variable
                - datatype full name (name of the futur directory)
                - hash value for storage purpose

        A special line define the default datatype.

        The line ordering is very important, since the last test is
        the one retained! For example, you may classify your variables 
        beginning with the a "c" character (it's not case sensitive, so 
        that the first column must be written with lowercase!) as follow:

        c       Char                    32
        cd      None                    0
        cl      None                    0
        clim    CLIM_Constant           8
        =def=   Real                    16
        
        meaning that a variable beginning with a "c" is a global character
        variable, unless it begins with "cd" or "cl" and therefore is a 
        local variable unless it begins with "clim" and then it's a
        constant.

        The "hash" value defines the number of files that will be created
        to store the variables of the matching datatype. The higher the
        number of variable is, the higher the "hash" value should be. But
        the higher this value is, and the longer the execution time will be 
        to produce the hypertexted image.

        Note that f2h_create checks for a fort_datp.$project file first,
        and if none is available, selects the default fort_datp.conf file.
        In any case, at the end of f2h_create, a fort_datp.$project file
        exists in the conf directory.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        6. Retrieving the original source code
        --------------------------------------

        By clicking on the [SRC] link (at the top of each file) you can
        retrieve a work copy of the original source code whitout any HTML
        extension.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        7. The job submission form
        --------------------------

        At the top of each element file, the [JOB] link opens the job
        submission form to perform a miscellaneous processing on the
        current element and its alternate versions.

        A @ (with spaces around) in the command line is replaced by all the 
        selected versions. If no @ is present in the command line, the
        versions are added at the end of the command.

        By default, there is no active pre-selected command. The preselected
        command are:
                a. diff ( unix diff between 2 files )
                b. diff3 ( unix diff between 3 files )
                c. diffbc ( diff performed only if differences are not blanks
                            and not commentaries )
                d. xterm ( spawns a xtern in the job working directory
                           including original source copies of selected
                           versions )
                e. vi ( same as xterm but automaticaly performs vi @ )

        WARNING: options d and e request your display to be present in
        - - - -  the command line.

        examples:
                - "for file in @ ; do echo $file; cut -f2- $file; done"
                - "myscreen" (xterm selected, perform 
                               xterm -display myscreen:0.0)

        WARNING: when executing a command through the Common Gateway Interface
        - - - -  you take the logname and permission of the "adm" login (or
                 something like this), so that you loose all your favorite
                 environment. The root manager should also be aware of this
                 gateway in the unix system security.
                 

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        8. The expand mechanism
        -----------------------

        When selecting [CPP] at the top of a source file code, a page
        is open where default include files are activated according
        to the current version of the file to expand. One can switch
        to other versions if any. The expand mechanism is performed through
        the cpp utility. 

        The default CPP variable is set to

                CPP="/lib/cpp -P"

        in the f2h_cgiexpr script. Feel free to modify it if necessary.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        9. Search variable mechanisms
        -----------------------------

        Only the variables which match the definitions of the fort_datp.conf
        file are statically referenced. As an example, according to rules
        coding, you can reference only the global variables (F77 common) of
        your sources.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        10. Warnings and bugs
        ---------------------

        - Do not forget to add the F2HBIN path in your .profile.

        - Include file names enclosed between single quotes (') after the
INCLUDE Fortran keyword are not recognized. Use a double quote or the
#include cpp statement.

        - Multiple subroutines inside a single source file cause serious 
          troubles.

        - It could happen that your *awk* command is not really up to date.
Very often the *nawk* command is then available so that you must alias
awk to /bin/nawk (or /usr/bin/nawk) for a proper use.

        - Your umask is set to 22 at the beginning of f2h_create.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

        For any remark or suggestion, or just to "register" as a user
        (without any kind of license agreement!), please send a mail to
        Eric.Sevault@meteo.fr

        A http site is available to retrieve up to date Fortran2html versions:

        http://www.meteo.fr/perso/eric.sevault/Fortran2html/index.html

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
</PRE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
