<html>

<head>
<title>Debian Install</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1>Debian Linux: Anatomy of a Successful Install</h1>

<hr>

<h2>What is Debian?</h2>

<p>Debian is a fairly recent distribution of Linux. Debian was an official
Free Software Foundation (GNU) project, but now is independent. The current
stable version is 1.2. "Debian" comes from "Deb and Ian Murdock;" Ian is
Debian's original developer.</p>

<p>I originally installed Debian 0.93, a beta release. Debian is now
officially released, an install manual is available, and the installation
tools are in much better shape than when I originally installed it. This
site is obsolete in many respects, but may still be useful, especially
to anyone upgrading from an older version of Debian.</p>

<p>For more information:</p>

<ul>

<li><a href="http://www.debian.org/">Debian Organization</a></li>

<li><A HREF="ftp://ftp.debian.org/pub/debian/">FTP archive at
ftp.debian.org</a>

<li><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/mdw/linux.html">The Linux Documentation
Project</a>

<li>the <a href="news:linux.debian.user">linux.debian.user</a> news group
or the debian-user mailing list (subscribe at
<a
href="mailto:debian-user-request@pixar.com">debian-user-request@pixar.com</a>);
the newsgroup mirrors the list (read-only).

</ul>

<hr>

<h2>And who are you?</h2>

<p>I am currently systems team leader (sysadmin/netadmin/etc.) at
<a href="http://www.gulf.net/">Gulf Coast Internet Company</a>,
and I maintain a Web server on the side as
<a href="/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

<p>I installed Debian on my <a href="system.html">home computer</a>, not the
one running this web server.</p>

<hr>

<h2>The Install</h2>

<p>My successful installation of Debian involved the following:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="disks.html">Obtaining the boot/root/base disks</a></li>
<li><a href="diskpart.html">Repartitioning my hard drive</a></li>
<li><a href="boot.html">Booting Debian and installing the base system</a></li>
<li><a href="net.html">Obtaining and installing the network packages</a></li>
<li><a href="packages.html">Obtaining and installing other packages</a></li>
<li><a href="other.html">Obtaining and installing non-Debian software</a></li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>The Upgrade</h2>

<p>Recently I upgraded to the Debian 1.1.2 release, ELF binaries and
the Linux 2.0.6 kernel. While a bit more troublesome than I had hoped,
it was accomplished quite easily thanks to Debian's packaging system.</p>

<p>The main stumbling blocks were:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>The package format changed incompatibly, so I had to first upgrade
from my old dpkg to an intermediate version, then from the intermediate
version to the latest version.</p>

<li><p>There are some sketchy upgrade notes on the Debian FTP site,
be sure to read them before upgrading from 0.93.</p>
</ol>

<hr>

<p>Brought to you by <a href="/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
