<head>
<title>Revolution Search</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Search the Revolution</h1>

<FORM ACTION="http://www.scimitar.com/cgi-bin/AT-revolutionsearch.cgi"
	METHOD="POST">

<p>Enter <INPUT TYPE="radio" NAME="mode" VALUE="concept" CHECKED> words
describing a concept or <INPUT TYPE="radio" NAME="mode" VALUE="simple">
keywords you wish to find information about:<br>
<INPUT TYPE=TEXT SIZE=40 NAME="search">
<INPUT TYPE=SUBMIT VALUE="Search">
<INPUT TYPE="hidden" NAME="sp" VALUE="sp">
</FORM>

<p><a href="http://www.excite.com/"><img
	src="/images/excite.gif"
	alt="Excite for Web Servers" BORDER=0></a>

<hr>
<H2>Tips</H2>

<p><b>Revolution</b> uses Excite for Web Servers, a concept-based
searching engine.</p>

<p>A query is simply a description of what you are looking for. If
you do a keyword search, Excite will return documents that have those
words in them. If you do a concept search, Excite does a more intelligent
search, returning documents that contain those words and related words.</p>

<DL>
<p>
<DT><B>Only use words that are relevant to your query</B></dt>
<DD>If you're looking for documents about the Widget2000, don't enter a
query like "<CODE>Find me all documents about the Widget2000</CODE>".
Excite for Web Servers considers <I>all</I> the words in your query to be
part of your information need, so queries like the previous example will
find all documents about <I>finding all documents about</I> the Widget2000,
which may not be exactly what you want.</dd>
<P>
<DT><B>Specify multiple forms of the same phrases</B>
<DD>Excite for Web Servers distinguishes between hyphenated and
un-hyphenated words. So, sometimes it might be necessary to explicitly say
that you want both versions, for example "<CODE>CDROM CD-ROM</CODE>". Excite
for Web Servers will try to figure out that <CODE>CDROM</CODE> and
<CODE>CD-ROM</CODE> are the same, but it never hurts to explicitly specify
multiple forms.</dd>
<P>
<DT><B>Common words are ignored</B>
<DD>Excite for Web Servers doesn't index common words like <I>a</I>,
<I>and</I>, or <I>the</I>.  Consequently, those words in your query will
be ignored. Excite for Web Servers also ignores numbers; however, it can
find strings that happen to contain a number, for example <I>3Com</I>.
</dl>

<p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
- <a href="/revolution/about.html">About</a> -
<img src="/images/revolution-sm.gif" alt="REVOLUTION" align=middle border=0>
