<head>
<title>My Debian System</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1><a href="index.html">Debian</a></h1>
<h2>The system on which I installed Debian</h2>

<p>I installed Debian 0.93R5 on my home computer. With Linux, just about
every component matters. You've got to make sure there is support for it
(see the Hardware HOWTO for details).</p>
<ul>
<li>AMD 486DX2/66 CPU
<li>20MB RAM (originally 8MB)
<li>515MB Western Digital hard disk
<li>3.5" floppy drive
<li>no-name Cirrus Logic 5428 video card
<li>Microcom V.34 28.8Kbps internal modem
<li>Conner TapeStor 250 QIC-80 tape drive
<li>Peak Performance 2-button mouse
<li>MAG Innovision 15" SVGA monitor
<li>Canon BJ-100 BubbleJet printer
<li>original OS: MS-DOS 6.22, Windows for Workgroups 3.11
</ul>

<p>I have a dialup PPP connection to the net.</p>

<p>Just a few examples of why components matter in a Linux install. The hard
disk gave me problems because it has more than 1024 cylinders. The video
card and monitor together determine how to configure X windows. The fax modem
is class 1, and requires class-1 compatible fax software. To use the printer I
needed an appropriate driver for GhostScript and had to configure lpr
appropriately. I strongly advise anyone considering a Linux install to do
a complete inventory of their system components!</p>

<hr>

<p><a href="index.html">Example Debian install</a> brought to you by <a
href="http://www.scimitar.com/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

</body>
