<head>
<title>Debian Disks</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1><a href="index.html">Debian</a></h1>
<h2>Getting the Debian Disks</h2>

<p>To install Debian from floppy you need five disks:</p>
<ul>
<li>Boot floppy: this boots Debian.
<li>Root floppy: this contains just enough of a system to run; bootdisk uses
this to run Debian so you can install Debian on your hard disk.
<li>3 base floppies: these contain the "base" package, the minimal Debian
system. Once installed on your hard disk, you don't need floppies anymore
(kind of).
</ul>

<p>"Images" of the above disks are available from ftp.debian.org
(and mirrors) under <a
href="ftp://ftp.debian.org/debian/stable/disks">/debian/stable/disks</a>.
The disk images are available for both 5.25" and 3.5" floppies
(1200* and 1440* respectively).</p>

<p>You can copy these images to disk using "dd" from Unix or "rawrite" from
DOS/Windows. Since I started with a Windows system, I downloaded rawrite, also
available from Debian archives under <a
href="ftp://ftp.debian.org/debian/tools/">/debian/tools/</a>.
I used rawrite to copy the images to five floppies.</p>

<p>There is also a CD-ROM available now from the <a
href="http://www.debian.org/">Debian Organization</a>.</p>

<hr>

<p><a href="index.html">Example Debian install</a> brought to you by <a
href="http://www.scimitar.com/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

</body>
</html>
