<head>
<title>Repartitioning for Debian</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1><a href="index.html">Debian</a></h1>
<h2>Repartitioning for Debian</h2>

<p>I have a 515MB hard disk that I wanted to hold both Windows and Debian.
Originally there was one partition (for Windows' C: drive) spanning the entire
disk. I wanted three partitions: 195MB DOS, 303MB Linux root partition and 17MB
Linux swap partition (strange numbers because of cylinder boundaries).</p>

<p>Step One in messing with your hard disk is backing up the entire thing. To
this end, I purchased a Conner TapeStor 250 QIC minicartridge tape drive. (Good
price from <A HREF="http://cexpress.com:2700/">Computer Express!</a>, much
better ones are even cheaper now.) I installed the drive and backed up C:.</p>

<p>Step Two in messing with your hard disk is to create a system floppy to boot
DOS. (When C: is gone, you won't be able to run anything that happened to be on
it.) So I created a system floppy (FORMAT /S A:) and copied FDISK.EXE and
FORMAT.COM from C:\DOS to the system floppy.</p>

<p>Next what is <em>supposed</em> to happen is that you boot with the system
floppy, use FDISK to delete existing partitions and create a new
(smaller) DOS partition. Then you FORMAT /S C:, restore from backup and move
on.</p>

<p>However, I had <a href="problem.html">problems</a> because my hard drive
has more than 1024 cylinders. In my case, the backup was the only useful thing
accomplished at this point. I had to create the DOS partition from Debian
and restore the C: drive later.</p>

<hr>

<p><a href="index.html">Example Debian install</a> brought to you by <a
href="http://www.scimitar.com/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
