<head>
<title>Booting Debian</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1><a href="index.html">Debian</a></h1>
<h2>Booting Debian and Installing Base</h2>

<p>Well now I have my bootdisk, rootdisk and three basedisks. My hard drive is
backed up and repartitioned to make room for Debian. The next step was to boot
Debian and install the base system.</p>

<p>Booting is easy. Stick the bootdisk in the drive and reboot. The bootdisk
ran fine, but gave one strange message: "No BIOS32 extensions present. This
release still depends on it. Sorry." I later found out from Michael Neuffer
that this only applies to a EATA/PCI/SCSI combination and can be safely ignored
in other configurations.</p>

<p>After the bootdisk is done, it asks for the rootdisk. The rootdisk put
me in cfdisk ("curses fdisk"), a nice screen-oriented program for installing
Debian (actually for messing with your hard disk).</p>

<p>Cfdisk presents a menu of nine steps that you must go through one
by one (except "show partition table" which you can do at any time). I don't
remember the exact wording or sequence, but it roughly followed this
outline.</p>

<ol>
<li><p>Change disk partitions. I had <a href="problem.html">problems</a> here
because I have a hard disk with greater than 1024 cylinders.
cfdisk wouldn't read my partition table correctly. What I wound up doing was
deleting existing partitions, then creating three partitions: 195MB for
DOS, 303MB for Linux root and 17MB for Linux swap.</p>

<p>I later booted DOS with a DOS boot disk, formatted the DOS partition and
restored my DOS C: drive to it.</p>

<p>Linux requires at least one partition for the root file system. A swap
partition is highly recommended. If you like, you can create other partitions
for other file systems such as /usr, /var and /home.</p>

<li><p>Activate swap. If you created a swap partition, this makes it used.</p>

<li><p>Install Debian base system. Put in the three basedisks
when asked, and Debian is on your hard drive.</p>

<li><p>Create bootdisk. This allows you to create a new boot floppy so that you
can boot from the root file system on your hard disk rather than needing a
separate rootdisk floppy.</p>

<li><p>Display partition table. Do this at any time to see what
partitions are on your hard disk.</p>

<li><p>Reboot system. Reboots don't work on my box; reboot flashes some
keyscan errors on my screen then hangs. Although the 1.2.9 kernel claimed
to fix the hang-on-reboot problem, it persisted on my machine even after
upgrading to 1.2.13.</p>

<li><p>Go to shell. Now you can actually use the system you just installed. In
reality, this is just to see that things are working. You'll want to boot from
your new bootdisk, and login at the prompt.</p>

</ol>

<hr>

<p><a href="index.html">Example Debian install</a> brought to you by <a
href="http://www.scimitar.com/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
