http://www.scimitar.com:80/debian/net.html 198.69.72.176 19970215100526 text/html 4420
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 15 Feb 1997 10:05:34 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4249
Last-modified: Tue, 08 Oct 1996 04:42:43 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>

<head>
<title>Networking Debian</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1><a href="index.html">Debian</a></h1>
<h2>Networking Debian</h2>

<p>By this point I was happy. I had the Debian base package installed on my
hard drive and I had a boot floppy to boot it. The next thing to do was to get
the packages that make the system usable: X windows, printer support,
development kits and so forth.</p>

<p>The problem is that while all the Debian packages are available on the
Internet, the base package doesn't include network support. If you want to
install from the net, you need to get the net packages first.</p>

<p>How I did this was to run Windows, download some basic packages (including
networking) to a single floppy, then boot Debian back up, copy the files from
floppy to the Debian filesystem, and install the packages.</p>

<h2>"Packages" in Debian</h2>

<p>Debian's nicest feature is "packages." Installation and maintenance of
software is simplified by having "package" files containing all the binaries,
configuration files etc. needed by an application. The "dselect" program
(along with the command-line "dpkg" that is uses) lets you install, configure
and remove all packages.</p>

<p>For example, the "lilo" package contains LILO, the Linux loader which allows
you to boot Linux (and other operating systems such as DOS/Windows) from your
hard disk. The lilo package file is "lilo-15-4.deb" which shows the package
name ("lilo"), the developer's release ("15"), and the Debian package release
("4").<p>

<p>Packages are stored on Debian archive sites in the "binary" directory. The
packages are organized into "sections" corresponding to archive directories.
For example, the "lilo" package is in the "system" directory (section).</p>

<h2>Choosing Minimal Packages</h2>

<p>I didn't want to keep switching back and forth from Windows to Debian, so I
wanted to download enough packages to let me work within Debian. At the same
time, I wanted to keep it down to one floppy if possible.</p>

<p>My choice of initial packages was:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>base/dpkg. You don't need to re-install any of the base software, but I
wanted to be sure I had a recent version of dpkg.</p>

<li><p>editors/elv-vi. Elvis is a vi clone (I'm an unreformed vi user).
The Debian base system now comes with ee, the "easy editor", but when
I installed it you had to add your own editor.</p>

<li><p>system/lilo. LILO lets you boot Linux from your hard disk so you don't
need a boot floppy. Major convenience.</p>

<li><p>net/netbase. The base Internet package for connecting to the net.</p>

<li><p>net/netstd. The standard Internet applications.</p>

<li><p>net/ppp. I have a PPP Internet account, so I needed the ppp package to
dial up.</p>

</ul>

<p>The above packages fit on one floppy with room to spare. Note that it was a
DOS floppy because I had to download them from Windows.</p>

<h2>Installing Packages from Floppy</h2>

<p>Installing from a DOS floppy involved:</p>
<ol>
<li>Boot Linux with Linux boot disk and login as root.
<li>Create directory to hold packages (e.g. /usr/local/packages).
<li>Mount DOS floppy: <samp>mount -t msdos /dev/fd0 /floppy</samp>
<li>Copy files from floppy to package directory:
<samp>cp /floppy/* /usr/local/packages</samp>.
<li>I renamed the files to their original names, although I didn't have to.
<li>Unmount DOS floppy: <samp>unmount /dev/fd0</samp>.
<li>Install each package with "dpkg."
</ol>

<p>I learned "dpkg" by trial-and-error, which wasn't too hard since it is
incredibly easy to use. For each package, I ran "dpkg --install
&lt;filename&gt;" which did everything. All I had to do was watch. You can also
run "dpkg --install --auto &lt;directory-name&gt;" which installs all ".deb"
files in the specified directory, but I wanted to follow things a little more
closely. Debian now comes with "dselect," a screen-oriented front-end to
dpkg.</p>

<p>After dpkg did its work, I <a href="ppp.html">configured PPP</a> and
connected to my Internet account. At this point I could download other
packages with FTP and work entirely within Linux.</p>

<hr>

<p><a href="index.html">Example Debian install</a> brought to you by <a
href="http://www.scimitar.com/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
