</DOCHDR>
<html>

<head>
<title>Installing Debian Packages</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1><a href="index.html">Debian</a></h1>
<h2>Installing Debian Packages</h2>

<p>Once I had LILO set up to boot Linux, and PPP configured so I could connect
to the Internet, I then set out to download and install more Debian
packages.</p>

<p>This was easier than installing the first (networking) packages, because
I could do everything from within Linux without needing floppies.</p>

<p>The process is simple: ftp to <a
href="ftp://ftp.debian.org/debian/stable/binary/">ftp://ftp.debian.org/debian/stable/binary/</a>,
get the package files you want, and run "dselect". When I installed,
dselect wasn't available, so I did "dpkg --install" on each one instead.</p>

<h2>Some Good Packages</h2>

<p>Some things come in handy early on. I would recommend getting the following
first.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>system/lilo. LILO lets you boot Linux from hard disk.</p>
<li><p>Your favorite editor. Mine is vi, so I downloaded editors/elvis, a vi
clone.</p>
<li><p>net/netbase, net/netstd and net/ppp. If you have a dial-up Internet
connection you need these.</p>
<li><p>text/groff, text/man. Lets you read manual pages.</p>
<li><p>admin/cron, devel/m4, devel/make. Some other useful things depend on
these.</p>
<li><p>x11/xbase, xbaseR6, xr5shlib, xfnt100, xfnt75, and an X server.
My video card uses the xsvga server package.</p>
</ul>

<p>After that, you can use your system comfortably while you get other stuff.
Developers will want most of the things under devel. Everyone will probably
want some more stuff from editors, tex and text for printing and text editing.
Mail, news and net contain Internet apps.</p>

<p>Some of the packages I installed include <a href="ftape.html">ftape</a>
and <a href="lpr.html">lpr</a>.</p>

<hr>

<p><a href="index.html">Example Debian install</a> brought to you by <a
href="http://www.scimitar.com/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
