<head>
<title>Installing Non-Debian Software</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1><a href="index.html">Debian</a></h1>
<h2>Installing Non-Debian Software</h2>

<p>After I had a nice Debian system up and running, I wanted to add software
that isn't "packaged" for Debian. That is, I needed to download and compile some
freely available packages.</p>

<p>Among the software I installed:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="apache.html">Apache</a>: HTTP server (since then,
	Apache has been Debian-packaged)</li>
<li><a href="pcsnd.html">pcsndrv</a>: Linux PC speaker driver</li>
<li>xv: image tool (now packaged and distributed in the "non-free" section
	because it is shareware)</li>
<li>Netscape: I think you've heard of this one (a package is now available
	that assumes you have downloaded Netscape, and installs it
	properly for you)</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<p><a href="index.html">Example Debian install</a> brought to you by <a
href="http://www.scimitar.com/">Scimitar Internet Services</a>.</p>

</body>
