<html>
<head>
<title>Party Cancun</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Party Cancun</h1>

<p>Cancun is one of the few places on Earth designed from the ground
up as a party town. If you like drinking and dancing, and have a ton
of money to blow, do it. Especially if you aren't sure about traveling
in a foreign country, Cancun is about as delicate a transition as you
can get from the U.S. without going to some boring cold place like Canada.</p>

<h2>Spirit</h2>

<p>Cancun displays a spiritual affinity with New Orleans,
only an hour or two away by plane.
The most obvious sign is the presence of N'awlins mainstays
like Pat O'Brien's, Fat Tuesday and Ruth's Chris Steak House.
Se&ntilde;or Frog's and of course Hard Rock Caf&eacute;
are in both towns.</p>

<p>One major difference is the music. Unlike New Orleans, Cancun is
very limited musically. Mexicans still haven't discovered the electric
guitar, and that syncopated upbeat gets annoying after a while. Great
stuff to dance to, though.</p>

<p>Most locals speak English, so you can get by, but Spanish is
definitely preferred.</p>

<p>All the hotels and clubs are on the strip of the island, known as
the Hotel Zone (<i>Zonas Hoteleras</i>). There is just one road, which
is great for drunks trying to figure out which way to go.</p>

<h2>What You Need To Know in Cancun (Abridged Version)</h2>

<ul>
<li><p>Bacardi is the cheap stuff in Mexico. Pick up
a few bottles of Cuervo, Kahlua and Bacardi cheap to take back home, and
try not to drink them before then. Well, maybe just <em>one</em>.</p>

<li><p>Mexicans are shy, until they get on the dance floor.</p>

<li><p>Never haggle unless you're sober. Imagine if car dealers could
switch between two currencies.</p>

<li><p>Most clubs are open all night long all week long, but weekends
are hottest, and Dady O's is the place to be after 2am or so.</p>

<li><p>Tequila slammers and Dos Equis beer (<i>cervesa</i>) should form
a large part of your diet.</p>

<li><p>The clubs and street musicians play the same ten songs over and
over again, three of which are "La Bamba." (Believe it or not, one of
the others is "Old MacDonald Had a Farm.")</p>

<li><p>Always take the bus (three pesos), unless you are too drunk to
remember where your hotel is, in which case take a taxi (agree on the
fare ahead of time).</p>

<li><p>Do drink the water. The hotels and shopping centers (<i>plazas</i>)
on the island have purified water. Off the island, don't take the chance.</p>

<li><p>If you're looking for the authentic Mexican experience, you're
in the wrong place. A day trip to downtown or Isla des Mujeres will
help satisfy your desire for foreign stimulation.</p>

<li><P>Snorkeling is cool.</p>
</ul>

<h2>Spanish for Partiers</h2>

<p>You don't <em>need</em> to know Spanish to party in Cancun, but
even a little helps. So few U.S. partiers even bother with <i>si</i>
or <i>gracias</i> that the locals recognize when someone respects the
place enough to try.</p>

<p>Luckily for drunks, Spanish follows simple rules, unlike English.
The same letters are always pronounced the same. Quick refresher: in Spanish,

J is pronounced like the English H (think <i>jalape&ntildeo</i>).

H is silent.

E is pronounced kind of like the A in SAY, even at the end of a word.

O is like the O in FOR.

L is L, but LL is Y (think <i>tortilla</i>).</p>

<p>Little bits of Spanish come in handy even when you speak mostly English:</p>

<ul>
<li><p><i>Si.</i> Yes. Don't say this if you don't understand the
question.</p>

<li><p><i>No.</i> No. Tough, ain't it?</p>

<li><p><i>Gracias.</i> Thanks. Say this about once every sentence.</p>

<li><p><i>Arrete.</i> Stop the bus. (You could push the button instead, but
this is more fun. Also <i>bajon</i> to open the back door.)</p>

<li><p><i>Uno dos tres quatro cinco seis siete ocho nueve diez.</i> You should
remember these from Sesame Street.</p>

<li><p><i>Ron.</i> Rum, as in <i>ron y coke</i>. With a lime,
<i>cuba libre</i>.</p>
</ul>

<h2>Etc.</h2>

<p>Whatever your style of partying, it's there and it isn't hard to find.
Enjoy.</p>

<p>The beaches, of course, are beautiful. Cancun is at the beginning of
the Caribbean. The water really is crystal clear and blue as the sky.
Reefs for snorkeling are plentiful with brilliantly colored fish.
Half-day or full-day tours to take you there are available all
over the place.<p>

<h2>Smuggling</h2>

<p>Leaving the U.S. is pretty easy. Have your birth certificate and driver's
license, and fill out a tourist card when you arrive. Entering Mexico
is <i>no problemo</i> -- even if you get the red light they just open
your bags and look without poking around.</p>

<P>Re-entering the U.S. isn't much more difficult if you look like a
tourist. You fill out a customs form listing what you have (you can bring
in $400 worth of stuff including one liter of alchohol with no duties).
Cuban cigars are strictly forbidden in the U.S., so hide them in your
luggage along with your other three bottles of liquor.</p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
