<html>
<head>
<title>Bars of Pensacola</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Bars of Pensacola</h1>

<p>Pensacola, Florida is best known for its white sand beaches.
Some of the most beautiful beaches in the world stretch along the
Florida panhandle, which starts at Pensacola and continues down
through Ft. Walton Beach and Destin to Panama City.</p>

<p>If you're ever in the area, and you should be, you might want
to check out some of the nightlife in the Pensacola area.</p>

<hr><h2>Seville Quarter</h2>

<p>The granddaddy of Pensacola partying, Seville is the place to
hang out. Seville is a collection of seven small bars housed in a
historic building in downtown Pensacola (built in the 1880's).
You pay one cover charge and stroll around through all the bars,
each of which has its own ambience. Or, if you're a real lush, you
become a member for $25 and get in free year-round.</p>

<p>Lili Marlene's is a tiny bar with dart boards and a stage where
Rick Holt and Blues for Your Mama can often be found playing. Good
for playing darts of course, and for drinking in small groups.</p>

<p>Fast Eddie's is the sports bar of the place, with pool tables,
a few TV sets and -- gotta be hip -- an Internet surfing station.
When they had air hockey here it was cool, now it sucks. The last
thing I want to do when I go out is look at a computer.</P>

<p>The Palace Oyster Bar and Restaurant, as its name implies, is
where you can sit down for a meal. You can order food anywhere though --
the Oysters Seville is a house specialty.</p>

<p>Phineas Phogg's is the dance club. Great place to wind up after
you've been drinking everywhere else. It also has a nice balcony
from which you can discreetly observe everyone dancing.</p>

<p>The End O'the Alley Bar is small, even by Seville standards, but
has the best beer selection (but no Dos Equis, damn). In the courtyard,
you can breathe the fresh air (or a cigar) while listening to a mediocre
reggae band.</p>

<p>Seville usually gets going around 10pm or so and lasts late.
Fridays and Saturdays are busiest of course, but even most weekdays
have some action. Wednesday evenings are business hour -- bring a
business card and get a free drink. Tuesdays and Thursdays 18-year-olds
can get in, otherwise 21-and-up only.</p>

<hr><h2>The Dock</h2>

<p>Chances are, if you're in Pensacola, you're going to the beach.
What do you do when you get there? Go to The Dock if you want to party.</p>

<p>Located in the heart of Pensacola Beach on Santa Rosa Island, directly
on the Gulf of Mexico, the Dock is the ultimate beach hangout. Enjoy
a view of the Gulf as you sip a frozen drink and listen to island music.</p>

<p>Sundays are rum-and-reggae days -- specials on rum drinks and
the best damn reggae band I've ever heard, Lazy Day. Lazy Day is the only
band I've heard that can do a good Marley cover. Their brand of reggae
includes island versions of old standbys such as "Brown Eyed Girl"
and rockin' versions of dance music. Guaranteed to get you on the
dance floor.</p>

<p>The Dock has a couple of pool tables, serves some decent fried
shrimp and oyster baskets, and employs some of the best looking waitresses
in Pensacola. One of the best ways to renew your appreciation of life
is to spend a Sunday at Pensacola Beach, hanging out on the beach til
evening, then heading to the Dock for dinner, a few games of pool,
more than a few Cuba Libres, and some kick-ass music.</p>

<hr><h2>Chan's and Coconut Bay</h2>

<p>These two are within walking distance so I'll lump them together.
Located in the northern area of Pensacola, these are close to the
malls and the University of West Florida. Kinda the college kid hangout.</p>

<p>Chan's has a volleyball court, dart boards and TV sets, and is also
a decent restaurant. They've started calling Tuesdays cigar nights, but
their cigar selection sucks and no one goes there to smoke.</p>

<p>Coconut Bay is probably the best dance club in Pensacola, which
is like saying the best Mexican restaurant in Idaho (not very difficult).
Nice mix of bar, dance floor and outdoor veranda.</p>

<hr><h2>The Cigar Brewery</h2>

<p>Oh yeah! It's about time. Pensacola finally has a cigar bar.
Unfortunately, it's kind of slow right now, but I expect that it'll
pick up soon with Spring Break right around the corner.</p>

<p>The Cigar Brewery on Zaragossa Street downtown is a laid back
cigar bar with a walk-in humidor and mac daddy beer on tap (Bass,
Samuel Adams, etc.). Jazz music plays lightly in the background.
The air filtration system is working better now, so you no longer
have to smoke more of everyone else's cigars than your own.</p>

<p>The humidor has a decent selection at decent prices (for cigars
these days). None of my favorites, but you can always get a Thomas
Hinds.</p>

<hr><h2>Bedlam's</h2>

<p>Pensacola's "rave" bar, also downtown, opens at 2am and closes
whenever. You bring your own beer, and pay to bring it in the door
(two bucks a six pack or something like that). Bedlam's is the whole
rave scene, so there are druggies and gays there. On the other hand,
drugged out lesbians can be fun to dance with.</p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
