<html>

<head>
<title>Hong Kong's Economic Policies</title>
<!-- Place: Hong Kong -->
<!-- Time: report 1993 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Hong Kong's Economic Policies</h1>

<p>1993, from Daniel Lam of Melbourne, <a
href="/revolution/by_place/Oceania/Australia/">Australia</a>:</p>

<p>Well, I was born in <a
href="/revolution/by_place/Asia/HongKong/">Hong Kong</a> and visited there
last month.</p>

<p>I know of no convenient reference for finding out about HK economic
policies, but you can always try the HK government, I guess.  Here I
will just present some facts which I discovered while there.</p>

<ol>
<li><p>Free Trade. There are no protective tariffs. There are import duties on a
few items for revenue purposes, alcohol and cigarettes, I think. Duties on
cosmetics was abolished on April 1, when the new budget came into effect.</p>

<li><p>Personal Income Tax. There is tax-free allowance of HK$56000 (about
US$7000). For income above that there is a single rate (I think) of about
15%.</p>

<li><p>Welfare. There is no social security scheme, and no unemployment benefits.
The only form of direct welfare I can think of which exists is old-age
pensions.</p>

<li><p>Economy. Unemployment is less than 2%. The "world-wide economic recession"
which mysteriously hit the world despite the best efforts of governments to
protect their peoples seems to have missed Hong Kong, whose government was
grossly negligent and didn't do a thing.</p>

<li><p>Labour laws. There are no minimum-wage laws like in the U.S., or, worse
still, the kind of centralized arbitration we have in Australia. There are
some laws and regulations governing safety and the like.</p>

<li><p>Health. There are public hospitals where very cheap subsidized health
care is available. There is no state health insurance scheme, nothing like
Medicaid or Medicare. If you want to get (almost) free health care, you go to
a public hospital and join the queue. If you go to a private doctor, you pay.
I should also say that the HK Medical Association, like the AMA, controls the
registration of doctors.</p>

<li><p>Education. There is compulsory education up until an age which I don't
remember. There are public schools and private schools but most schools are
privately run religious schools subsidized by the government.</p>

<li><p>Guns. HK has draconian gun-control laws. It is a British colony, after
all.</p>

<li><p>ID cards. All HK residents are required to have and carry with them a HK
identity card. Visitors are "advised" to carry identification with them. This
measure is intended to catch illegal immigrants from <a
href="/revolution/by_place/Asia/China/">China</a>, who are sent back
immediately, unless they claim asylum or refugee status and succeed.</p>

<li><p>Housing. A lot of people (something like 25%) live in government housing,
although the government is trying to move them to private housing. This doesn't
stop the private real estate market from boiling constantly. Real estate is
extremely expensive, and is rising constantly. Almost everybody in HK lives in
a flat. Houses are only for the fabulously rich. I had great difficulty in
comprehending the notion of a "suburb" when I first came to Australia.</p>

<li><p>Shopping. This is the most important thing. There are no restrictions on
hours of trading. Shops are open on weekends and late into the night.</p>

</ol>

<p>As you can see from this list, HK has a very high degree of economic freedom,
and quite good personal freedom, excellent compared with its neighbours. Four
more years to go ...</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
<a href="/revolution/">Topics</a> -
<a href="/revolution/by_place/">Places</a> -
<a href="/revolution/by_time/">Times</a> -
