</DOCHDR>
<html>

<head>
<title>Planes, Trains and Automobiles</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Planes, Trains and Automobiles: Humor</h1>

<hr>

<h2>O'Rourke on Car Safety</h2>

<p>A car used to be a simple piece of machinery, something like a very fast
rider mower but better because you couldn't mow the lawn with it. You started
this up, drove off at pretty much any speed you desired, and then exercised
a variety of constitutionally guaranteed liberties, usually by having sex and
accidents.</p>

<p>No more -- nowadays if a car cannot survive a fall from the Gateway Arch
and emits any vapors more noxious than Evening in Paris, the federal
government won't let you own it, and what they will let you own you can't
really drive, because fifty-five miles an hour is the speed at which a
spirited person parallel-parks, not motors to
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/il/Chicago.html">Chicago</a>.</p>

<p>-- <a href="/revolution/by_name/O/PJORourke.html">P.J. O'Rourke</a>,
in <cite>Republican Party Reptile</cite></p>

<hr>

<h2>Barry on Speed Limits</h2>

<p>I'd also like to see speed limits that take into account what song
you're listening to on the radio. Ideally, if a police officer pulled
you over for doing, say, 95 mph in a 75 zone, and you could prove
to him that you were listening to the Isley Brothers' version of
"Twist and Shout," he would not only have to let you off, but he would
also be required, by law, to sing along with you.</p>

<p> -- <a href="/revolution/by_name/B/DaveBarry.html">Dave Barry</a>,
in <img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
href="http://www.goflorida.com/davebarry/db010796.htm">"Speed vs.
Limits"</a>.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
