<head>
<title>Canadians Tiring of Benefits</title>
<!-- Place: Canada -->
<!-- Time: 1990's -->
</head>

<h1>Canadians Reconsidering 'Benefits'</h1>

<p><a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/Canada/">Canada</a> in recent
decades began practicing the Santa Claus form of
government, giving its citizens an extensive package of welfare benefits,
from a comprehensive national health care system to generous welfare
allowances.</p>

<p>The predictable outcome of this has been huge increases in government
spending and debt, the steepest tax hikes in any industrialized nation,
income stagnation and rationing of "public" goods.</p>

<P>Federal and provincial Canadian governments are finally seeking to
cut spending in an effort to reduce taxes and debt. Prime minister Jean
Chretian expects significant cuts in health spending, welfare, pensions,
child care, homeless shelters and other entitlement programs.</p>

<p>The libertarian-leaning Reform Party made huge gains in the 1993 elections,
becoming the third-largest party in the lower house of Parliament, after
the Liberal Party and the Bloc Quebecois. The Conservative Party is also
doing well.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: N.Y. Times News Service article "Canadians reconsider rising
costs of benefits," in the September 18, 1995 <cite>News and
Observer</cite>.</p>

