<head>
<title>National Service</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: 1993-1996; report released March 1996 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Clinton Puts "Service" in National Service</h1>

<p>When Bill Clinton was elected President in 1992, one of his pet
projects was AmeriCorps, a pie-in-the-sky program administered by
the newly created Corporation for National Service. AmeriCorps was
going to help students pay their way through college by volunteering
for good causes.</p>

<p>Typical of modern day boondoggles, the National Service program was
not presented as yet another massive bureaucracy handing out the dole,
but as an "investment" in the future of the country, funded by a
"public-private partnership".</p>

<p>In March 1996, less than four years after the program's inception,
the corporation's own inspector general announced that the program's
financial books were in such sorry state that they could not even
be audited. The corporation had incomplete and inaccurate records,
did not maintain adequate security over financial data, and ignored
some of the most basic rules of money management.</p>

<p>Not coincidentally, the cost per participant, orginally estimated
at $18,000, turned out to be $27,000.</p>

<p>In 1995, the corporation received nearly half a billion dollars in
government funding. That wild-eyed radical Republican-controlled Senate
recommended slashing that to only a measly four hundred million or so.
This fits in with the Republican motto: "We want a slightly smaller
government than we have today, but bigger than the one we had yesterday."</p>

<p>Libertarians oppose national service programs because:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>As evidenced above, they needlessly waste enormous sums of
taxpayer money. Whether they waste $400 million or $500 million is
not a useful distinction.</p>

<li><p>In the U.S., national service is not one of the duties assigned
to the federal government by the Constitution. One does not "phase out"
unconstitutional activity, one stops it.</p>

<li><p>"Voluntary" national service programs eventually lead to
a mandatory draft. When proponents see segments of society they don't
like (the rich for example) being underrepresented by volunteers,
they propose a draft to make sure everyone does their "fair share."</p>

<li><p>Government is unsuited to charity and compassion.
Government is force, government is prison, government is the barrel of
a gun. Any government-run attempt at providing charity is doomed to
failure, creating only dependency and undesired incentives.</p>

</ul>

<hr>

<p>Source: March 13, 1996 Associated Press article, "Accountants unable
to audit books of Clinton pet project," reprinted in the
<a href="/revolution/by_name/N/NandO.html">NandO Times</a>.</p>

