<head>
<title>House Passes Free Speech Exception</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: June 28, 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Free Speech, Except ..</h1>

<p>Republicans and Democrats have trouble with freedom. A <em>little</em>
freedom is fine, they say, as long as there are exceptions.</p>

<p>On June 28, 1995, the U.S. House approved a proposed constitutional
amendment to ban flag-burning. The measure passed 312-120, well over the
two-thirds majority required.</p>

<p>The Senate must also approve the measure by a two-thirds majority for it
to be sent to the state legislatures, three-fourths of which must approve it
for the amendment to become part of the Constitution.</p>

<p>The amendment would allow Congress and state legislatures to "prohibit
the physical desecration of the flag of the United States."</p>

<p>Libertarians believe in freedom, period, no and's, if's or but's. There's
no such thing as half-way freedom. Either you make your decisions, or someone
else makes your decisions. Congress and state legislatures have no moral
authority to tell individuals what they can do with their own property,
including flags.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: June 28, 1995 Associated Press story.</p>

