<head>
<title>The Internet</title>
<!-- Place: global -->
<!-- Time: 1969 - present -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>The Internet</h1>

<p>The Internet will rank with the printing press and the automobile as
innovations that revolutionized society. Science, government, commerce,
recreation and politics are all moving in new directions as the result of
the Internet. Information services are already estimated to comprise 50%
of the U.S. economy.</p>

<p>The encouraging thing is that the Internet is empowering individuals.
Hell, any old yahoo can set up his own web site and reach the world (see,
for example, <a href="/revolution/">Revolution</a>). As should be
expected, governments worldwide are trying to restrict the Internet and
its effects.</p>

<p>Topics:</p>
<ul>
<li>March 1995: <a href="hkraid.html">Hong Kong shuts down
	Internet providers</a></li>
<li><a href="malaysia.html">Malaysia offended by Internet</a></li>
<li><a href="vietnam.html">Vietnam prepares for Internet</a></li>
<li><a href="arabs.html">Arab countries try to censor Internet</a></li>
<li>February 1996: <a href="china.html">China limits the Internet</a></li>
<li>February 1996: <a href="/revolution/express/techno/exon/">U.S.
	passes Internet censorship</a></li>
<li>March 1996: <a href="singapore.html">Singapore licenses Internet
	providers</a></li>
<li>March 1996: <a href="tempo.html">Banned Indonesian magazine goes
	online</a></li>
<li>March 1996: <a href="laundry.html">Official criticizes anonymity
	of cash transfers on Internet</a>
<li>May 1996: <a href="strike.html">French ISPs protest arrests
	with Usenet strike</a>
<li>June 1996: <a href="uae.html">United Arab Emirates call for
	more Internet restrictions</a></li>
</ul>

