<head>
<title>BATF Harasses Sporting Goods Store</title>
<!-- Place: Marin County, California (USA) -->
<!-- Time: January or February 1991? -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>BATF Harasses Businessman for Maintaining Rights</h1>

<p>The BATF revoked the Federal Firearms License (FFL) of a sporting
goods store owner who refused to comply with an illegal request.</p>

<p>As reported by Neal Talbot in the March 1, 1991 <cite>Gun Week</cite>,
Kirby Ferris was contacted by the BATF to schedule an inspection of his
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ca/Marin.html">Marin County</a>,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ca/">California</a> sporting
goods store. A BATF agent said the BATF
would inspect his records and check his list of customers "against the crime
computer."</p>

<p>Ferris knew that the Form 4473's that firearms purchasers fill out is
supposed to remain private except when a particular weapon has been used in
a crime or a particular purchaser is a suspect.</p>

<p>When the BATF arrived to conduct the inspection, Ferris, along with four
witnesses and a video camera, asked the BATF to sign a release holding
Ferris blameless for the BATF's violation of the Privacy Act of 1974 (improper
use of confidential information). The BATF refused to sign the release and
left.</p>

<p>The BATF warned Ferris to submit to the warrantless search. Ferris wrote
Harry Alder, the local head of the BATF, demanding that he "cease and desist"
and pointing out the federal statutes making such a search illegal.</p>

<p>Alder responded by revoking Ferris' FFL and threatening him with up
to $250,000 in fines and 5 years in prison. Ferris demanded an administrative
review (part of due process) but was refused.</p>

<p>The warrantless inspection is part of the BATF's "Operation Forward Trace,"
which a federal judge has prohibited in his <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/oh/">Ohio</a> jurisdiction
pending a final
ruling in a court case involving the tactics.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
