<head>
<title>U.S. Assault Weapons Ban</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: May 5, 1994 -->
</head>

<body>
<h1>U.S. House Passes Assault Weapons Ban</h1>

<p>May 1994, from Release 1.11 of the Online Report to the Firearms Coalition,
Box 6537, Silver Spring, MD 20916 (Copyright 1994 by Neal Knox Associates,
P.O. Box 6537, Rockville, MD  20916. Reproduction and distribution of this
bulletin by any means is encouraged so long as this statement is retained.):</p>

<p>House-Passed Gun/Magazine Ban</p>

<p>Following is the Judiciary Committee version of <a href="hr4296.html">H.R.
4296</a> which passed the House 216-214 May 5, 1994.</p>

<p>It has numerous subtle but significant changes from the
Feinstein amendment included in the Senate-passed crime bill. 
Either of the versions, or a combination of the two, will be folded
into the House-Senate conference committee compromise.</p>

<p>The conference committee will probably reach an agreement
within two weeks, then each house will have to approve their
compromise.</p>

<p>Both bills prohibit possession of over-10-shot magazines and
"feeding devices," or the parts from which one can be made, which
were manufactured after the effective date (with exceptions for
police and military, or retired law enforcement officers given a
magazine -- or gun -- by his agency).  New over-10 magazines would
have to be serial numbered and clearly marked as made after the
effective date.  "High capacity feeding devices" would be
classified as firearms.</p>

<p>There is no criteria as to how a person would prove that a 15-
shot Beretta or Ruger pistol magazine, or a 20-round AR-15
magazine, were legally possessed prior to the effective date.</p>

<p>The Senate-passed version requires owners of affected guns to
record ownership by registering that gun with a dealer within 90
days.  Such registered guns could subsequently be transferred by
obtaining a Form 4473 from the buyer, then permanently keeping it. 
The 4473 used for registration would have to be kept with the gun.</p>

<p>Failure to comply with the Senate-required provisions would be
punishable by 6 months in jail, $1,000 fine and permanent
prohibition from possessing any firearm.  An unregistered gun would
be contraband.</p>

<p>The House-passed version does not include the requirement that
presently possessed guns be registered.  It does require that the
seller of a grandfathered gun obtain a Form 4473 from the buyer. 
In the subcommittee Chairman Charles Schumer changed that to allow
BATF to designate any form, raising concerns that they might
require the same form used for the transfer of a machine gun.  </p>

<p>In the full committee Schumer offered an amendment striking
the prohibition on ownership for someone who failed to keep proper
paperwork, and stated he would insist on that change being put into
the final conference committee bill.</p>

<p>Also in full committee he assured Rep. Glickman that
"unmodified sporting handguns" like the Glock, Ruger P-89 and
Beretta 92F wouldn't be affected by the bill.  After the meeting I
told Glickman that Schumer hadn't told him the truth, since those
guns could not be manufactured and sold for the over-10-shot
magazines for which they were designed.</p>

<p>On the floor, to win the vote of someone, Schumer made a vague
promise to remove all the record-keeping requirements on
grandfathered guns.  Chairman Jack Brooks told the House that such
a commitment couldn't be kept because similar requirements were in
both bills.</p>

<p>The 19 named models include the Intratec TEC-22, TEC-9, TEC-
DC9; AK-47S from several makers; Uzi and Galil; Beretta AR-70; SWD
M10, M11, M11/9 and M12; Colt AR-15; FN/FAL, FN/FLR, FNC; and Steyr
AUG.  Also banned are lookalikes "of any caliber."</p>

<p>According to ABC, President Clinton got
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/nc/">North Carolina</a>
Congressman Steve Neal to sign on by promising that only those 19
guns would be banned.  If so, he lied, for BATF has written Sen.
Larry Craig that the generic definitions apply to 45 "currently
advertised" models, and Gun Week has listed 184 guns that would be
affected.</p>

<p>Affected guns are:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Semi-auto pistols which have a detachable magazine and two
or more features such as a barrel shroud, threaded muzzle, or
magazine other than in the grip, or which weigh over 50 ounces
unloaded;</p>

<li><p>Semi-auto rifles with a detachable magazine and two or more
features such as a folding or telescoping stock, protruding pistol
grip, bayonet mount, flash suppressor, grenade launcher attachment,
or threaded barrel muzzle;</p>

<li><p>Semi-auto shotguns with a fixed magazine over five rounds,
an ability to accept a detachable magazine or drum, with a pistol
grip extending below the action, or with a folding or telescoping
stock.</p>
</ul>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
