<head>
<title>Repeal of U.S. Assault Weapons Ban</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: April 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Repeal of Assault Weapons Ban</h1>

<p>After the Republicans regained control of the U.S. House and Senate in
November 1994, they made repeal of the Clinton Weapons Ban a top priority.</p>

<p>Republican-controlled committees held weeks of hearings at which people
testified to the value of guns including assault weapons in self-protection.</p>

<p>In April 1995, several U.S. House Republicans and Democrats introduced H.R.
1488, calling for repeal of the ban, guarantee of individuals owning any
firearm in their home for self-defense, increasing penalties for "criminal
misuse" of firearms, and directing U.S. attorneys to increase prosecution of
criminals using firearms.</p>

<p>The repeal of the ban is obviously a step in the right direction. The others
bring up more questions than answers. What types of firearms are guaranteed to
be legal? What determines use for self-defense? Does "criminal misuse" of
firearms include violations of minor BATF regulations which shouldn't exist in
the first place?</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
