<head>
<title>Bosnia and Russia</title>
<!-- Place: Bosnia -->
<!-- Time: September 8, 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Yeltsin Warns of European War Over Bosnia</h1>

<p>As NATO conducted an air assault of <a
href="/revolution/by_place/Europe/Bosnia/">Bosnian</a> Serbs,
<A href="/revolution/by_place/Asia/Russia/">Russian</a>
President Boris
Yeltsin warned that continued military intervention by Western nations would
result in a new war in
<a href="/revolution/by_place/Europe/">Europe</a>.</p>

<p>"In future we will have to respond adequately and help the Serbs," Yeltsin
said. "I have already signed a decree on humanitarian assistance. If these
attacks continue, then things will become much hotter ...
Those who insist on the expansion of NATO are making a major
political mistake. The flame of war would ignite across all of Europe."</p>

<p>Yeltsin's tirade is probably hot air to appease reactionary forces in
the Soviet, excuse me, Russian government, but that very fact points up the
instability of Russia's political situation.</p>

<p>Even when you don't consider the futility of intervening in a centuries
old religious and ethnic conflict, is it worth risking a nuclear war to
intervene in some backward global outhouse of a region?</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: London <cite>Times</cite> article "Yeltsin steps up threats to
NATO," reprinted in the September 9, 1995 <cite>News and Observer</cite>.</p>

